tion></semantics></math> protons, which gives <math xmlns:q="http://cnx.rice.edu/qml/1.0" xmlns:fo="urn:oasis:names:tc:opendocument:xmlns:xsl-fo-compatible:1.0" xmlns:m="http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML" xmlns:md="http://cnx.rice.edu/mdml" xmlns="http://cnx.rice.edu/cnxml"><semantics><mrow><mrow><mrow><mstyle fontstyle="italic"><mrow><mtext>Zm</mtext></mrow></mstyle><mfenced close=")" open="("><mrow><msup><mrow/><mn>1</mn></msup><mtext>H</mtext></mrow></mfenced></mrow></mrow><mrow/></mrow><annotation encoding="StarMath 5.0"> size 12&#123; ital &quot;Zm&quot; left (&quot;&quot; lSup &#123; size 8&#123;1&#125; &#125; H right )&#125; &#123;&#125;</annotation></semantics></math>, or <math xmlns:q="http://cnx.rice.edu/qml/1.0" xmlns:fo="urn:oasis:names:tc:opendocument:xmlns:xsl-fo-compatible:1.0" xmlns:m="http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML" xmlns:md="http://cnx.rice.edu/mdml" xmlns="http://cnx.rice.edu/cnxml"><semantics><mrow><mrow><mi>Z</mi></mrow><mrow/></mrow><annotation encoding="StarMath 5.0"> size 12&#123;Z&#125; &#123;&#125;</annotation></semantics></math> times the mass of a hydrogen atom. Thus the binding energy of a nuclide <math xmlns:q="http://cnx.rice.edu/qml/1.0" xmlns:fo="urn:oasis:names:tc:opendocument:xmlns:xsl-fo-compatible:1.0" xmlns:m="http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML" xmlns:md="http://cnx.rice.edu/mdml" xmlns="http://cnx.rice.edu/cnxml"><semantics><mrow><mrow><mrow><msup><mrow/><mi>A</mi></msup><mtext>X</mtext></mrow></mrow><mrow/></mrow><annotation encoding="StarMath 5.0"> size 12&#123;&quot;&quot; lSup &#123; size 8&#123;A&#125; &#125; X&#125; &#123;&#125;</annotation></semantics></math> is
    
